"The concept of identifying codes was introduced by Karpovsky, Chakrabarty and Levitin. We call any subset \\(C\\subseteq V\\) an (r, ≤ k)-identifying code if the sets {c ∈ C | d(c,v) ≤ r, v ∈ F} are distinct for all subset \\(F\\subseteq V\\) with at most k vertices. Here, V denotes the vertex set of graph and d(c,v) the number of edges on any shortest path from c to v. We prove a new lower bound \\(\\frac{5}{12}\\) on the density of (1, ≤ 2)-identifying codes and construct a (2, ≤ 2)-identifying code with density \\(\\frac{2}{7}\\) in the infinite king grid."
